A Republican strategy to impede Obama's re-election
The Republican leaders justified their policy for the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth and states that electoral fraud is less frequent in the United States than the number of people dying from the fall of a ray.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the rate of participation.
In that regard, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike what happens in Canada, the American states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And in that same line, a majority of American governments promulgated, starting in 2009, new laws that hindered the registration or voting process.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 elections, which saw the increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
Accordingly, 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced during 2011.
The new electoral laws require voters to present an identity document with a photograph, in addition to an American citizenship test.
On the other hand, these laws reduce advance voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of the poll and withdraw their right to vote to citizens with a criminal record.
Before the 2006 elections, no American state demanded that voters present a photographic identity document.
The Indiana State was the first to demand it.
The United States Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of Indiana's law.
The Republican authorities therefore rushed to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to present an identity document with photography.
It is important to bear in mind that, contrary to what is happening in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as the Social Security Card.
In fact, 11 per cent of American citizens, i.e. 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photographic identity documents issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with these characteristics.
But often, obtaining the required identity card costs more than $100.
Thus, new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25 per cent of African Americans, 15 per cent of people who earn less than $35,000 a year, 18 per cent of citizens over 65 years of age and 20 per cent of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have a photographic identity document.
And there's still more.
In many states students, the voters who vote most for Democratic candidates, cannot use the identity document with photography issued by their institution.
Moreover, the same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs who often vote for Republican parties to use documents issued by such clubs.
Before 2004, no state required the citizenship test to vote.
Arizona was the first state to present such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws that require voters to demonstrate that they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit Hispanic vote.
It seems that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic party.
On the other hand, Republican legislators supported in 2011 certain laws that abolished the registration of voters on the same day of the scrutiny in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a support service for voters who would like to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of about 10 million citizens.
The measures taken since 2009 resulted in a fall in the registration rate for new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators adopted laws in five other states that favoured the reduction of the advance voting period.
For example, in the 2008 elections in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, while the latter represented no more than 13% of the state voters.
In the case of Hispanics, the same thing happened exactly.
They represent no more than 11% of the voters, equivalent to 24% of the citizens voting in advance.
However, whites, representing 76 per cent of the electorate, represent only 46 per cent of the citizens voting in advance.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters have fervently opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
In this regard, the Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Public Prosecutor's Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
In part, damage could be limited.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states adopted the law requiring the presentation of a photographic identity document.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democrat critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted, as it is clear that they intend to influence the results of 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states that have adopted these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to achieve the presidency.
It is too early to affirm with certainty whether these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the rate of participation.
In this regard, measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
