There is, in this great world, a widespread and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to violate that rule and don't try too hard, because it will end up hurting itself.
Although particle physics are a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics: the principle of Pauli's exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" that consists, grossly, of some of its characteristics.
Physicians classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we meet the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli's beginning.
And on the other hand there are the bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists that has no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means that they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Laboratory's website The Particle Adventure, which is, by the way, extraordinary, the bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, of which we won't talk here, and the "power particles", by which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
These bosons, you could underline here, they're not the exotic bugs we could believe.
In fact, if you succeed in reading this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinaryly banal boson: the photon or the "light particle" that acts as a "mensager" of the electromagnetic force.
