Bitcoin differs from other systems with types of virtual coins such as "credits", used to advance a video game and that can be won playing or can be bought (and even sometimes exchanged).
The Facebook social network also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange a central authority controls and deals with changes.
With the bitcoin, all network nodes are both depositaries of accounting books, verifiers, currency issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is electronically signed through a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the bitcoins changes are included in the public account book, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This is through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to computers and the winner, a sort of interim central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a file trimming phase, i.e. the transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique numerical footprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "troce" the set.
The aim is to find the number that offers a particular print (more zeros at first).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructably linked to the chain of sets of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit a fraud, one user would like to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would remain orphaned, as both have different prints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided into two regularly, likely before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but are divided up to the hundred millionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in calculating power.
The life of the network already has its heights.
