A Constitution with Forceps in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which provisionally gives it full powers, he decided to play the whole for all.
He surprised everyone on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote for its final text the next day.
Only a week ago, the head of State had given that Assembly two more months to complete its work.
And it has been almost two years since Egypt has used a provisional text, several times modified, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial embroidery.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president persevere in his "self-critical delusion" and continues to "treat his word" and "scroll the right".
On the part of its supporters, it is ensured that this is a measure to speed up the institutional and political crisis and accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held within the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that compels the Brothers to renounce their project to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, this is also a way to regain a popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversial causes ravages throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in their favour, as stated in an interview with American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "or they vote my text or I keep the full powers", powers that will supposedly come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment in which 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, the majority of Islamist, voted yesterday.
Most of the liberals did not come to the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they believed that they could not assert their views.
The representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, substitute members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to Muslim Brothers.
As was expected, the articles voted unanimously.
On the other hand, commentators are pleased that one of the few discrepancies of the day has been expressed practically at the time of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the Constituent's watch was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday afternoon, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2 of the Constitution of 1971, which stipulates that "the principles of the Sharia constitute the principal source of law, remains the subject of all considerations".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "the principles" could be replaced by "the rules", which would have allowed stricter implementation.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
The liberals call it hypocrisy and consider it to be nothing but an advertising artifact.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer in particular to article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University a consultative role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm their conformity with the laws of the Shariah.
According to the Egyptian specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "people called to pronounce themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we see the premises of a theocracy."
The fears of the liberals are also increased by the fact that the next rector of the university would be rather less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution we are in the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not Ulemas but university, some of them trained in the French system," explains Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But it recognizes that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, as the terms used imitate the religious vocabulary.
"We refer specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that could be raised in the future would be to what extent civil judges are competent to pronounce themselves above all this."
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday received many criticisms regarding the extended powers conferred on the President of the Republic.
Muslim Brothers will claim that they are few compared to those who were during the previous regime.
Another conflicting point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the revision of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
The prosecution of civilians in military courts, as requested by human rights associations, will also not be prohibited.
These also showed their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticated.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, stresses Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing was the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word was not contained in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president had to go out on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this noon.
The supporters of the Head of State expressed themselves on Saturday.
