How much the offices, such as NKÚ, operate there the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Accounts), with an organization similar to ours, with a school as well, the only thing is that in their case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices evolve parallel.
The competences are also to a certain extent analytical, however, while Germany has a federal organization, the Courts of Auditors are even at this level. In this regard it differs slightly from our system.
The Federal Court of Accounts (BRH) can only control federal money, which we here call state funds.
The public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are controlled by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to make a comparison without specific data. However, Germany remains a model in some respects, but it cannot be specified exactly where it is best.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of the inspectors?
I'm sure not, but, I repeat, I don't like to make such comparisons.
It must be said that even those countries that we take as a model must face a large number of problems.
If it wasn't, it wouldn't be any benefit for you to work with our office, would it?
With regard to our country's legislation, what did the amendment to the law on public procurement mean to your Office? Is its incidence manifested in any way?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been stated in the control procedures.
Since we carry out ex post checks, there is a certain delay.
For now, it is noted in the process of preparing for future controls: we have started a new tool for "non-economic risk detection", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public awards, which have been analysed.The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are changed, the conditions of some types of the selection process and similar.
Do you think that the adoption of this law is beneficial, or rather an embezzlement to the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope it is.
The problem that may arise is that the regulation "hardens" and that it is impossible to comply with it.
Already under the previous regulations, controlled persons were linked to the contractor (e.g. in the case of regional operational programmes of the regional council), and each law that was not respected in the area of public procurement meant a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to tighten the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who commit a formal failure, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We'll see where this path starts.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the ODS would not bother employers with controls of the so-called švarc system, with reference to being autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the švarc system forbidden or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits anything, then even the Prime Minister of the Government cannot prevent the Office from acting that has an obligation to carry out such controls and to require obligations.
He can say, "We change the law and allow it," but he can't say that we'll do like nothing.
In the law on public procurement, the regulation is rather strict as to how it should be formally acted, and that is how it should be in order to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic to exclude the candidate with the best offer for failing to meet the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This is, in my opinion, what we lack.
