Šimon Ornest: At our concerts we want to accumulate positive energy
It is said that in a little less than a month the world will come to an end, what do you think about it?
It's just one of so many other alarming news that we like to grab.
The music group The Tap Tap rather likes to make jokes about this and we like to say that we are the only music group in the world that manages to gather enough positive energy to postpone the end of the world or to avoid it.
In addition, in December you organize a truly original project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you explain to our readers?
This is a state charity act we've been planning for two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential that has the end of the Maya calendar announced for December 21 at 11:10 in the morning.
The previous day, on December 20 at 21 hours, we will organize 3 simultaneous concerts in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end at approximately the same time as the Maya calendar ends on Kiribati Island, in the Pacific Ocean, 12 hours ahead of our time zone.
Who did this idea come up with?
Initially it was my idea, then we were forging the project all together with our designer Honza Augusta.
In addition to wanting to gather enough positive energy and avoid the end of the world, we also want to reflect, together with society, on the state in which we will leave the world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Maya calendar we have also created a unique collection of articles: boots, t-shirts, bags and original keyboards against the end of the world that can be purchased at www.e-tap.cz, another way to support us.
The Tap Tap group, along with other interpreters, also sang the so-called hymn against the end of the world, which bears the title "End of the world, cancelled".
It is now very popular on YouTube, can you hear it at charities?
Of course it will, and it will be just the last, well, as long as everything goes well and the world doesn't end...
All interpreters will sing it at the same time at the three concerts.
The hymns will link together simultaneously thanks to the special live broadcast on Czech Television.
Tomáš Hanák has written the lyrics of this song and plays the leading role of Jesus in the video clip, where he also sings Xindl X...
How did this collaboration arise?
We work together even with other figures from the Czech cultural scene, besides organizing many charities and concerts...
We make every effort to participate in this project.
Most of them have been shown to be interested and have fun working with us.
What will the money raised at the concerts against the end of the world be for?
To equipment for the educational center without barriers Studieo, which we have completed in its sixth consecutive year with the civil association Tap in Jedličkęv ústav.
Students at the Jedličkęv ústav school regularly receive a visit from teachers with whom they carry out fun and interesting activities.
Students do not have sufficient financial means to pay teachers and we are making efforts to make it possible.
In the context of the completion of the works in Jedličkęv ústav, there will be an independent building to which we will move with this project.
A number of groups and interpreters perform at each concert.
What are the selection criteria?
We are trying to develop a programme that is attractive to all generations, including children.
For example, in Prague, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Barta, The Tap Tap, Marian Bango and Jiří Suchý will act.
For more detailed information, see www.kpks.cz.
Do you have any other similar "dramatic action" planned in the future?
In May we will act for the first time at the Pražské jaro festival, so here we will surely prepare an attractive program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to play at the Bohemian National Hall in New York and me, personally, taking advantage of that we are in the United States, I would like to complete it with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not exactly minimalist, so far you have acted for example in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is, however, a group of persons with disabilities.
How is the logistics and organization of these trips?
It's not as difficult as it may seem at first sight.
There are five members in the electric wheelchair, the chairs must travel in the luggage compartment and we also bear a lot of weight, the boxes with the instruments...
However, so far we have managed well. ČSA and British Airways were perfectly prepared, which keeps me surprised.
Even in Moscow, where we have recently returned, everything came out smoothly.
Thanks to the departures abroad you can compare the different attitudes of society towards the disabled and other aspects.
What have you met so far?
In Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, everything works better than here; in Russia we have witnessed that, in the east, there is a long way to go.
Unlike Prague, Moscow is full of barriers, there it is still uncommon that a person moves alone through the city center in an electric wheelchair.
Something as common as it is, for example, giving preference to someone in a wheelchair in an elevator, there it is not.
Fortunately, a civil partnership has been established that strives to theme the problems of persons with disabilities.
In what respect should we take an example of more developed countries?
There's a lot of things we're going behind...
But it is important to mention that the improvement and improvement of the situation always depends on the people directly affected.
In London and Madrid it is very normal that people with a serious disability move on their own in public and can go to the service, to the museum, wherever they want to...
But it is not very common for a large number of people with disabilities to participate in social life actively, in this regard, with The Tap Tap let's go a little ahead!
A society respectful or without barriers is one thing, but when the time comes when eminent athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers emerge, it will start to change everything really.
So far, they are isolated cases of people who have a great will force.
The Tap Tap group is currently very popular, but if we look a few years ago, what led you to form the group in 1998?
I entered as an educator in Jedličkęv ústav, where I had a lot of young people around me who wanted to dedicate themselves to something.
And since I'm a musician, I play, among others, the saxophone, I founded an amateur group with a co-worker.
And over time, as our moderator Laja Angelovič says, we got a little out of hand (laughter).
However, popularity did not come until the last few years, or am I wrong?
It is true that it helped us quite well to connect with famous singers and also work actively to promote the group.
We come to the conclusion that the work that is not seen is as if it did not exist.
Thanks to the European Union's assistance, we can also afford to be a teacher of quality, equipment, etc.
Did you intend to get that far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning I saw the potential that there was, that you can do something differently.
The world of the show is full of things that resemble each other.
It is logical, in its way, that all new things are welcomed with caution and it takes a long time to accept themselves.
There are few extraordinary things, but I dare say The Tap Tap is one of them.
The impression of someone who sees us for the first time is clearly compassion, it's a natural reaction...
But compassion is totally superfluous because people with disabilities are not abandoned beings who suffer and of whom we should have compassion.
There are people who are able to live a full life and develop, with the condition, of course, that they have the necessary means.
I always say that if something goes well for people with disabilities, then it's not just a breakthrough for them, but for society as a whole.
Did you help the fact that you're a demanding boss, as many people describe you?
If we want to do a quality job, we have to be rigorous in many respects and demand some discipline.
I think it's completely normal.
Some people come with a romantic vision and head in the clouds and when they find out they have to go two days to rehearse, go to the preparatory test and spend a lot of time traveling and in concerts, the initial euphoria quickly abandons them.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and get something.
Currently, The Tap Tap Group has twenty members.
How many of them were already in the beginning of 1998?
Only one: Laáa Angelovič.
We're an open group, people come in and out, you can't help it.
Whoever has will and desire will always find the doors open
