Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency last week Poland was accepted as twelfth member of the ESA. It is the second member country of the ESA of the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland initiated an intensive collaboration with ESA in 1994 and in subsequent years participated in the agency's project commission.
However, Poland's path to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in flights to space before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, the conference of A. Šternfeld at the astronomical observatory in Warsaw, in which, on December 6, 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the indifferent assistants and, years later, Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch prize for his "Introduction to cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great driver of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, he was known all over the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when he put his name on one of the craters of the hidden face of the moon.
Already in 1925 a dresine was built in Poland that was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is not known who was the author of the proposal and the outlines of the project are not known either.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used for the start of the dresin or for its braking.
The information about this dyresin is limited to the press collection of the time.
From 1933 onwards, the Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to missiles.
The research was funded by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
On the basis of the material preserved, it becomes clear that the investigation reached the stage of practical evidence.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the study "Rakieta - torpedo powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza", by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all project missile techniques for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The November 1954 edition of Problemy magazine refers for the first time to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronautics.
In one of them, Prof. M. Subotowicze, he proposed the creation of a society that would be dedicated to cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with future prospects.
Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish Society of Astronautics (PTA) aspired to become part of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of the same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice president of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He held this charge until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM probe rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and first launched on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had an apogee of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg in weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959 the two-step RM-2 rocket air tests began in the Błędów desert.
The rocket was 1,4 meters and weighed about 11,5 kg.
Another type of developing rocket was going to be the subject of real scientific study. RM-34 rocket was going to have a peak of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the high wind.
However, work was suspended in 1962.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the 1962s and 1965s.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which were differentiated by the space available for scientific devices.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for the volume was 0.4 litres, in the Meteor-1B of 0.34 litres and in the Meteor-1C of 0.62 litres.
The peak in all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first air tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km high.
Subsequently, Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also necessary to mention Poland's entry into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
Within the framework of the Interkosmos programme, Poland joined the cosmic space research on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonauta after Vladimír Remek.
The suspension of the law on social work is not the solution.
Last week the constitutional court suspended the law of social labour.
The resolution aroused a heated discussion in society.
It will certainly be interesting to examine the problem from a broader perspective.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalized world, are based on the principle of greater economic competition and less regulatory.
Consequently, this means that different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, along with unbridled financial speculation.
The impact of large differences on labour costs (wages) produces economic tensions.
Under this concept, it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the import of cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and thus "provokes a fall" in the competitor's price with the aim of making the most of the market and thus increasing its profit margin.
On a large scale it means, for most entrepreneurs, moving production abroad, buying there cheaper or disappearing.The result is high unemployment in those countries where the labour price, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and, by doing so, it is not responsible for the unemployment that this phenomenon generates, the social spending of the state necessarily increases.
This whole situation is conducive to the total disinterest of employers in paying taxes and compensating for the economic and social damage they have caused in their efforts to obtain benefits.
The situation is universally so well known that no specific statistical data is required.
Unscrupulous private capital practices create situations, in certain economies, in which the Governments of these countries are forced to compete with the objective of artificially reducing the social level of the population itself and thus attracting foreign capital to the country.
In other words, Governments make private capital available to their own population without taking into account social decline.
This is evident above all in the changes in existing laws.
The aim is to force the population to accept the dictation of private capital, especially in terms of wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other hand, through the restricted right of employees to work rights.
The result is growing poverty along with increased gaps between the poor and the rich.
For a number of years, there have been food delivery points for poor people in Germany that cannot be maintained with their own work.
The number of people receiving this type of aid is already million.
In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there is a rather frequent case: people employed with such a low wage that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum necessary to survive.
A scandal of this kind related to the situation of the auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament was made public.
The savings measures of virtually all the southern states of the EU undoubtedly lead to the same situation. People, pressured by an abysmal decline in their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the nineteenth century or to migrate with a bad wage on the edge of society, hoping that someday they will reach the private capital investor country.
Is it necessary to wonder where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty moves from one country to another or never arrives, as Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, Turkish, Moroccan, Egyptian or Africans continue to work for a small part of a European wage.
This also affects all Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media affirm even the satiety that the state should not bring capital to the economy, which leads to the economy's failure.
The private capital defends with nails and teeth the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by intruding in control.
It is then necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence its selfishness in political progress and, therefore, throughout the state.
In this case, the answer is clearly affirmative.
The proof is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and omnipresent, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that manifests itself in the field of corruption, in mutual favors, in legislation that is practically reprobable everywhere but not punishable.
In Germany, the situation is as follows: State ministries, in the absence of financial means, are responsible for drafting bills to private legal enterprises, which are often linked to industry.
This type of bill is then passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
Thus, all power does not emanate from the people, as announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups that represent their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation are quickly in a situation like that described by the Appians in their work The crisis of the Roman Republic in the times of Caesar and Pompeii: "The state had been disintegrating for a long time and the administrations were dealing with force."
In exchange for bribes, illegitimately obtained favors and helps to finance stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption spread unhinderedly and people went to the polls with the vow beforehand."... "There were no people in character who aspired to a post in the administration, so once, because of this disorganization, the state was eight months without consuls"... "He began to speak seriously that the only remedy for such a serious situation was autocracy and that it was necessary to choose an energetic man"... Although Appians thought of Pompeii, Caesar went up to power and transformed democracy forever into autocracy.
The conclusion, as in antiquity, is that the current company is based on disregarded preferences of the individual benefit without taking into account the common interests.
Private capital is not able, in its essence, to understand and claim the benefits of society as a whole.
The result is the same as that of then, an unprecedented decay of the elite, without an effort being made to reform it in depth.
The causes of the boom of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unbridled liberalization of economic systems in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
With respect to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of a liberal democracy, as a definite pause, pending the next coup.
The really devastating fact is that the current elite completely ignores the loss of hundreds of thousands of lives, social and humanitarian catastrophes that we have witnessed, as well as the crimes against humanity, as we know them in ancient and most recent history.
Suspension of the public procurement law is not the solution; at least not in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both at international and within the EU level, the Czech Government will be forced to continue to look for other ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution goes through concrete socio-political reforms, which strengthen both the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
