In November 1979, a group of the demonstration of Islamist students occupied the American embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats as hostages.
His release was to be in exchange for the dethroned shah Mohamed Réza Páhlevi, who after the revolution fled to the US, a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration, the situation did not offer any positive prospects: throwing the shah overboard could not be allowed, since, if it did, endangered the confidence of its allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the constitution of the theocratic regime, was not within its reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which subsequently intensified even more with the failed attempt to release the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were released 444 days after the Algerian government's negotiating intervention.
In the U.S., its fate caused a wave of solidarity and animation against Iran.
The failure in Iran contributed decisively to the defeat of Jimmy Carter in front of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film "Argo" by the director and actor Ben Affleck theme an episode of this story, which saw a little success for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated journey, they ended up at the residence of the Canadian embassy.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, helping a covert story: they went out with Canadian passports, as members of the film team that examined localization in the country for filming a superproduction of science fiction.
Combination of genders
The plan that the "exfiltration" expert drew from Toni Mendez required Hollywood's collaboration.
To make the lie seem true, it was written about the film project in specialized journals, press conferences were organized, the fictional production society even had a real office.
The details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is a unique combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other hand, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that went well, a deception (an example may be the Ocean's Eleven series).
The film combines the moods. We find well documented sequences of Tehran on one side. The credit sequence shows emblematic photographs of the time of events, which were reflected in the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other hand, typical Hollywood scenes slightly lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And besides, scenes at the CIA headquarters and other institutions: men dressed to analyze the situation at the negotiating table, in the hallways of the office, by phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been mocked, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Adiós, Adiós" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film in which the action does not take place in the city of Boston, where it was raised.
Also, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed the directors of ancient films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck proves it in Argo, where Tehran "wheels" in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of the true events. The introductory sequence of the embassy's taking is impressive because of its synoptic capacity which, at the same time, transmits the emotion of confusion and the lack of prediction that arises when, somewhere, history takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect on the fictitious scenes (the impostor team in the Tehran bazar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story does not offer much in the cinematographic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
And he manages quite well. Sometimes he adds something to reality: here everything doesn't come out so elegantly (the scene that stalks the crisis at Tehran airport, the deviation of a call to America and the unbridled search behind his track become a madness).
Argo's weakness is the discontrol that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are not, much less, the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck's film loses a bit of a dramatic trait, but it is a film that can be followed with moderate interest, value its realization and the retro style of a thriller evoking the 1970s.
But if it collapses, that'll be hard.
As an evocation of a real history and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omniscience of secret services can be, it is sufficient.
