The MVRDV architecture study shows that true adventures are not only in the head - in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the recently completed "book Mountain" - 2 photos
"I think the building is fun, it looks futuristic, and at last there's something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by who passes through the street.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician in a large company located near the library, points out: "In addition, the building is beautiful."
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have Internet, tablets and electronic books.
No one gets into those old-fashioned libraries by taste, right?
Spijkenisse, a bedroom town located at the gates of Rotterdam that hardly deserves a leaking visit, has the doubtful honor of having lifted up with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 people has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this embarrassing situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture and to copy the seven fictitious bridges represented on euro banknotes in the form of decorated miniatures of armed concrete.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that's how the political leaders decided that there was only one possibility to improve statistics: there was a library to be built!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, a master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for fun buildings to the pair that cynical, took the theme with his usual serenity and appeared to the presentation of the contest in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And as the jury looked perplexed around him and shrouded his shoulders, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here you have it, my proposal for the Spijkenisse Book Mountain, the so-called 'Boekenberg'."
Nine years later, the EUR 30 million mountain rises at the planned location.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of housing and townhouse buildings.
In early November the Book Mountain was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
In this way, the small city without history, which to date had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and an incredibly ugly town hall after whose white façade one would rather intuite a dairy center, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long way to the book
The first impression is that it is a paradise of books under a quest.
Well it is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountainous massif, but true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but prefer to melt with their topography at every step from their climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is luminous and easy to cover with the view, the brick floor collected and the elegant lamps unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
Upon view you can see the park banks, dogs and boys and girls playing soccer.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"Normally the book shelves are arranged along the façade and in the center opens a huge dark room that is usually uncomfortable and impersonal," Winy Maas says.
What we have done is to put the classic spatial configuration upside down and remove the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well exploited: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention deserves the black shelves that assume the functions of wall coating, parapet and barandilla at the same time.
View, touch, and smell are strange.
Even architects and civil engineers more a day shake their heads when they hear of this unknown material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project leader in the city of Spijkenisse.
And that's how one day, in a friesy farm, we encounter the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, in greenhouses and in the fields of the Netherlands, a plastic fabric of few millimeters of thickness is used as a basis for sustaining the roots of crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine tissue lasts two seasons and then is discarded.
For the library, this fabric was worn, for the first time in such quantities, up to four centimeters thick plates.
With heat and pressure, so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a mixture of new car and sports slipper.
After 105 feet you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain awaits us the reward: from the cafeteria you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but in it you can also enjoy some tasty Dutch croquettes and its ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant environment that maintains atmospheric moisture suitable for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a New Soul
"Although it is difficult to believe it given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling are obtained from geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is located under a huge glass pyramid, even in the sunny days the sun shines only for a few hours inside it.
The huge wooden fences located in a cross-cutting direction to the crystal facade serve to give shadow and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable interior climate.
The rest is the thing about automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptic worker in the Information Technology sector, has already dared to put his foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has also been there.
Similarly, Chinese traditional medicine teacher Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library. She calls "Boekenberg" as Spijkenisse's "late soul".
The reason is that, on the occasion of the opening that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way, it is intended to fill the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its complete archive; it currently has 70,000 copies.
The concept has deepened.
The shelves are full.
"There's nothing worse than a half empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I believe that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain link with this building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of the library.
Even if I'm just there to decorate.
In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved a complete success in that discipline that reigns that in the specialized argot is known as "creation of an identity".
The city of Spijkenisse has written a piece of the history of literature.
Regardless of how young and insecure it may be.
Finally a starting point to shape your identity.
