Bradley Manning didn't report ill-treatment, according to prosecutors.
Prosecutors try to deal with Bradley Manning's allegations of abuse during his prison stay
The trial focuses on the Manning period in Quantico military prison in Virginia
The defense wants the case dismissed on the grounds that Manning's incarceration was severe.
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
The prosecutors tried to prove on Friday that soldier Bradley Manning, accused of the greatest leakage of confidential information in the history of the United States, lost multiple opportunities to denounce the ill-treatment he now claims to have suffered while under military detention.
During the interrogation that the prosecution conducted to Manning at a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney-General Ashden Fein stated that the records of the weekly visits of the unit officers that Manning received for nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaint about the treatment he received.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing following the defence's request for the dismissal of the case, given that his imprisonment had been harsh and that that had already entailed sufficient punishment, came one day after Manning had testified that he had thought of suicide while in detention.
The army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
Later, WikiLeaks posted the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of information.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that the officers filled after the visits to Manning during his arrest at the military prison in Quantico, where he was imprisoned in maximum detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers would have asked Manning questions and scored their answers.
When Friday Fein asked about the forms, Manning recognized that he had qualified the treatment given to him by the celers as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facilities in general as "very professional".
The forms do not show any allegations of ill-treatment, although the officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he received, Fein said.
Manning responded that he had expressed concern about some issues and that the officers visiting him had discussed these problems and indicated that they would be addressed, but that they did not record those issues in the register.
"They wrote 'no incidences' (after having talked about the problems) but this doesn't necessarily mean that I wouldn't have mentioned any problems," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel of the Army Denise Lind, also asked Manning why she had not denounced the treatment she received during the January 2011 meeting with a council to examine the intentions of suicide she had expressed in a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain the reduction of the "prevention of injuries" regime under which he was under.
The military said that they had placed him under this restrictive regime, which is below that of monitoring for possible suicide, to ensure their protection and security for others.
"I wanted the old state to know that I was okay and (I wanted) to stop being under injury prevention... so that I could enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for almost two months before being transferred to the military prison at the base of the Marines in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said that he had considered suicide in Kuwait and that on one occasion he lost consciousness due to the heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world fell only to the Arafjon Camp, to that cage," Manning explained on Thursday.
"I thought I was gonna die in that cage."
Manning claimed that, once moved to Quantico, he spent most of the days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, some chancles, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he was trying to move all the time, as it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed that he always had a light coming from outside pointing to his eyes while sleeping.
He said that if the keelers couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they woke him up to turn again.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint about Manning's treatment.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth military prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation he had made in the Thursday statement, according to which, after having been forced to sleep naked one night in his Quantico cell, he was forced during a morning count to stand naked in front of the celers and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's interrogation on Friday, Manning said that he deduced by the order given to him by the celer that he should drop the blanket he could have covered with, but he recognized that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he did not pose a danger to himself.
Manning claimed that he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or his chanclas to self-injure but he had not.
Manning testified that that night he had removed his underwear, his chanclas and his glasses from his cell.
Her lawyers hoped that the judge would at least take into account the experiences she had experienced during her stay in prison and drastically reduce her sentence in case she was sentenced to the war council, which was scheduled to begin early next year.
The defence stated that it intends to make Manning guilty of minor offences and defend other accusations considered too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has argued that Manning was held under the rules of application to any detained person who is in maximum custody in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, illegally provoking the publication of information on the Internet, leakage of national defence information and theft of property or public records.
If you are found guilty of all charges, you may face life imprisonment.
